Based on the search results, I found comprehensive information about using the maven-plugin-testing-harness with JUnit4 and MojoRule. Here's what I found:

## Maven Plugin Testing Harness with JUnit4 MojoRule

The maven-plugin-testing-harness supports JUnit4 through the MojoRule, which is an alternative to extending AbstractMojoTestCase and is available when using JUnit 4.10 and later.

### Basic Setup Example

Here's the complete example from the official Maven documentation:

```java
import org.apache.maven.plugin.testing.MojoRule;
import org.apache.maven.plugin.testing.WithoutMojo;
import org.junit.Rule;
import static org.junit.Assert.*;
import org.junit.Test;

public class MyMojoTest {
    @Rule
    public MojoRule rule = new MojoRule() {
        @Override
        protected void before() throws Throwable {
        }
        @Override
        protected void after() {
        }
    };

    /**
     * @throws Exception if any
     */
    @Test
    public void testSomething() throws Exception {
        File pom = rule.getTestFile("src/test/resources/unit/project-to-test/pom.xml");
        assertNotNull(pom);
        assertTrue(pom.exists());
        MyMojo myMojo = (MyMojo) rule.lookupMojo("touch", pom);
        assertNotNull(myMojo);
        myMojo.execute();
        ...
    }
}
```

### Key Features

1. **@WithoutMojo Annotation**: When you don't need the functionality in every test method, you can use the @WithoutMojo annotation to skip rule executions.

2. **Maven Dependency**: Add maven-plugin-testing-harness to your pom.xml with test scope:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugin-testing</groupId>
    <artifactId>maven-plugin-testing-harness</artifactId>
    <scope>test</scope>
</dependency>
```

### Known Issues and Limitations

There are limitations with JUnit5, as "MojoRule can't be used because JUnit5 doesn't use @Rules anymore". However, for JUnit4, the MojoRule approach works well.

There have been documentation bugs noted, with some methods like getTestFile() not existing on the MojoRule class, and the example documentation having issues.

### Alternative Approaches

For more advanced configuration, you can use `lookupConfiguredMojo()` method: `this.mojo = (FoobarMojo)this.mojoRule.lookupConfiguredMojo(mavenProject, "foobar")` to properly populate project variables.

The official Apache Maven plugin testing repository on GitHub contains the complete source code and examples for the maven-plugin-testing-harness, which can be found at the apache/maven-plugin-testing repository.

